<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06143108 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06143108 </ACCESS><LEADPARA>  Employers in four states with family leave laws report little troublecomplying with them, according to a study released today. Only 9 percent ofthe companies surveyed in Minnesota, Wisconsin, Rhode Island and Oregonreported difficulty, said the Families and Work Institute, a New York researchgroup financed by foundations, corporations, unions and government agencies.;   The survey finding disputes one of the main arguments against the federalfamily leave legislation now before Congress -- that American businesses willsuffer economically if forced to provide workers time off for the birth of achild or a family illness.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  FAMILY-LEAVE STATES REPORT LITTLE TROUBLE  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Washington News in brief  </MEMO><BYLINE>  From Mercury News Wire Services  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Stock Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910522  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  May  </MONTH><PG.COL>  8A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  100  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday May 22, 199100143108,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>